Okay, during the day I hung up the new nest box. Here's how it looks in the garden.
But let's take a slight step back. "What's inside?" seems no one has asked.
The top is an ESP32 camera board with a fish-eye lens camera, and an infrared LED light that I removed from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The plastic box has an odd shape because the sides of the nest box can rotate. I bought it like that, and it couldn't be modified, so I had to design it based on that.
Since there is no power supply in the garden, the entire setup is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 lithium battery.
I didn't take a photo of the battery or the charger, but this is a photo of the solar panel.
The gray box attached to the side of the nest box contains the battery.
After being fully charged, it can run for about 4 hours.
I call this feature "special functionality." This way, the birds also have a bit of private space.
At first, I wasn't sure if the network in the garden was strong enough to support this setup. The old access points I replaced last fall definitely weren't good enough.
But the new access point has no coverage issues.
